issue.title: [Help] Validating different roles / security requirements per endpoint
issue.body:
Hi,

I can't seem to find the best way to do this in the documentation and I would appreciate any/all pointers if I've missed it!


My problem is the following:

I want to secure separate REST endpoints in the same javalin-pac4j application with different requirements.
I need to check for certain UserProfile claims in some cases (e.g. 'editor') but only check _isAuthenticated_  for other endpoints.
Do I need to create separate SecurityConfig with _separate_ handlers and add these to the Javalin Route configuration or is there way to use the same SecurityConfig and access several separate handlers at method/API route level?

A lot of the configuration is else reusable, the user will be submitting the same tokens, so it would be nice to avoid re-duplicating the security configs.


Best regards

issue.title: Fix SPNEGO performance issues

comment.body:
@mmoayyed I have made more tests when the pool is quickly exhausted by this configuration:

```yaml
cas.authn.spnego.pool-size: 1
cas.authn.spnego.pool-timeout: PT1S
```

and this command: `ab -k -c 30 -n 200 http://localhost:8080/cas/login`

And I have fixed the source code to take into account the fact that the `authentications` can be null when the pool is exhausted.

Everything should be good now.

-   Deprecate `LocalVariableTableParameterNameDiscoverer` completely (avoiding its exposure in native images) [#​29531](https://togithub.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/pull/29531)

issue.title: [Help] Validating different roles / security requirements per endpoint
issue.body:
Hi,

I can't seem to find the best way to do this in the documentation and I would appreciate any/all pointers if I've missed it!


My problem is the following:

I want to secure separate REST endpoints in the same javalin-pac4j application with different requirements.
I need to check for certain UserProfile claims in some cases (e.g. 'editor') but only check _isAuthenticated_  for other endpoints.
Do I need to create separate SecurityConfig with _separate_ handlers and add these to the Javalin Route configuration or is there way to use the same SecurityConfig and access several separate handlers at method/API route level?

A lot of the configuration is else reusable, the user will be submitting the same tokens, so it would be nice to avoid re-duplicating the security configs.


Best regards

issue.title: Fix SPNEGO performance issues

comment.body:
@mmoayyed I have made more tests when the pool is quickly exhausted by this configuration:

```yaml
cas.authn.spnego.pool-size: 1
cas.authn.spnego.pool-timeout: PT1S
```

and this command: `ab -k -c 30 -n 200 http://localhost:8080/cas/login`

And I have fixed the source code to take into account the fact that the `authentications` can be null when the pool is exhausted.

Everything should be good now.

-   Reorganize and modularize the Testing chapter in the reference manual [#​29522](https://togithub.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/issues/29522)

issue.title: [Help] Validating different roles / security requirements per endpoint
issue.body:
Hi,

I can't seem to find the best way to do this in the documentation and I would appreciate any/all pointers if I've missed it!


My problem is the following:

I want to secure separate REST endpoints in the same javalin-pac4j application with different requirements.
I need to check for certain UserProfile claims in some cases (e.g. 'editor') but only check _isAuthenticated_  for other endpoints.
Do I need to create separate SecurityConfig with _separate_ handlers and add these to the Javalin Route configuration or is there way to use the same SecurityConfig and access several separate handlers at method/API route level?

A lot of the configuration is else reusable, the user will be submitting the same tokens, so it would be nice to avoid re-duplicating the security configs.


Best regards

issue.title: Fix SPNEGO performance issues

comment.body:
@mmoayyed I have made more tests when the pool is quickly exhausted by this configuration:

```yaml
cas.authn.spnego.pool-size: 1
cas.authn.spnego.pool-timeout: PT1S
```

and this command: `ab -k -c 30 -n 200 http://localhost:8080/cas/login`

And I have fixed the source code to take into account the fact that the `authentications` can be null when the pool is exhausted.

Everything should be good now.
